  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Dedication Text for the Raising of the Beam at the National Confucian School
  author: Lee Chang-yong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The banner of Confucianism flies high and glorious—behold, the nation's fortune rises with it. When we rebuild the halls of learning, we must seek out the auspicious peaks and waters. Yet in this early time of crossing the river, we could not linger to choose the perfect ground. So we fashioned a sanctuary from the local schools, made a pavilion for study. Now that the capital is established, we have raised a hundred walls and set all in their rightful place. The geography speaks for itself—this one region stands distinct and complete. Fortune granted us leisure, and so we planned. We found fertile ground on Flower Mountain and removed the grand structure to Locust Market. In a moment, the gleaming pillars and fragrant courtyards rose—beautiful beyond measure! These waters like silk and peaks like spiral shells are where noble talents mature.

    We lift the great beam! Let songs of praise ring out:

    Young ones, gaze to the east of the beam—see how fair branches grow in the Cassia Palace, how this land gathers the spirit of excellence. Youth after youth bows in reverence to the Three Ministers.

    Young ones, gaze to the west of the beam—let the state of Qi transform into the state of Lu. From the Five Schools, wise scholars gather teachings close. Here we honor the worthy and exalt virtue, transforming all people.

    Young ones, gaze to the south of the beam—mountains low before my eyes, within reach of hand. Let the classics spread open, let questions pass between seekers. Who speaks without end of subtle truths and lofty discourse?

    Young ones, gaze to the north of the beam—the jade-toned and golden-voiced virtue of the Master himself! Yan Hui yearned to perceive it, yet found himself always behind. How can we truly comprehend it?

    Young ones, gaze above the beam—the roasted phoenix nourishes the worthy. Many scholars, refining themselves together, walk the great path and gaze up at high mountains in reverence.

    Young ones, gaze below the beam—when Confucian learning is honored, even the Five Hegemons grow ashamed. The royal way must reach even here, and our sovereign shall ride forth to this sanctuary.

    Humbly we pray: After this beam is raised, let teaching flow forth and filial piety flourish. Let benevolence and righteousness thrive, let ritual and music abound. Spread wide the six virtues to embrace distant lands with gentle care. Nurture talented hearts to strengthen our foundation and govern well. May our way grow ever greater, may peace settle upon all lands. Ten thousand years, ten thousand years to our sovereign!
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'beam-raising' ceremony (상량, sang-liang) was a significant construction milestone in traditional East Asian architecture, often accompanied by celebratory rituals and auspicious proclamations.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Five Schools' (오학, o-hak) refers to the five divisions of the National Confucian Academy where students studied classical texts.
  - key: ''
    value: References to the states of Qi and Lu invoke the classical period of Confucius, suggesting educational transformation and moral renewal.
  - key: ''
    value: Yan Hui (안회) was Confucius's most accomplished disciple, representing the ideal student forever seeking deeper understanding.
